In order to assess the cricketing and financial acumen of the different teams in buying players, we begin by considering the case of the Kolkata Franchise. As Table 4
shows, this franchise bought six players who committed to play for the entire season of whom one was a wicket keeper (Taibu), two were bowlers (Sharma (I) and Kartik (M)), two were batsmen (Ganguly and Hussey (D)), and one was an all-rounder (Agarkar). The performance of this squad, as measured in performance units, over the 2008 IPL season was 69.5 and when combined with the $3,567,500 that the franchise spent on these six players yielded an average cost of $51,330 per unit of performance (Table 5
).
